beration war (1954–1962) and war on civilians (1988–1999), this book challenges temporal and geographical frameworks that have implicitly organized studies of cultural memory around Euro-American reference points. Jarvis shows how this literature rewrites history, disputes state authority to arbitrate justice, and cultivates a multilingual archive for imagining decolonized futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican literature (French)xHistory and criticism. 0aCollective memory and literaturezAlgeria. 0aCollective memoryxPolitical aspectszAlgeria. 0aFrench literaturezAlgeriaxHistory and criticism. 0aImperialism in literature. 0aLiterature and historyzAlgeria. 0aPolitics and literaturezAlgeria. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021 Englishz978311075411708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021z9783110753882oZDB-23-DSP40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147802141440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021414423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021414/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075411-7  EBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DSPb2021